                        "displayName": "Wes McKinney",
                        "active": true,
                        "timeZone": "America/New_York"
                    },
                    "body": "Looking at this a little bit. From a \"cleanness\" point of view I think we should explore option 2 a bit more thoroughly. If we introduced a \"growth strategy\" template argument then this could theoretically be done with good code reuse. \r\n\r\nThere are some questions like how to handle the differing output type. In the chunking case, its a vector of arrays. In the non-chunking case, it's a single array. So you'd have something like:\r\n\r\n{code}\r\nclass Int16Builder : public ArrayBuilder, public internal::NonChunkedBuilder<Int16Type> {\r\n public:\r\n  using _Impl = internal::NonChunkedBuilder<Int16Type>;\r\n\r\n  using _Impl::Append;\r\n  using _Impl::AppendValues;\r\n  // etc\r\n\r\n  // Implement the ArrayBuilder public API\r\n  Status Finish(std::shared_ptr<Array>* out) override;\r\n};\r\n{code}\r\n\r\nI've suffered enough from {{extern template}} visibility issues that I'd like to avoid going down that rabbit hole if it can be avoided\r\n\r\nObviously this is not urgent work -- I place it in the bucket of future performance optimization (I would guess that chunking at the 16MB/32MB granularity will improve the performance of many applications)",
